* {{ill|Enoshima Shrine|ja|江島神社}} (Fujisawa City, Kanagawa Prefecture, Enoshima, one of Japan's Three Great Benzaiten Shrines) * {{ill|Zeniarai Benzaiten Ugafuku Shrine|ja|銭洗弁財天宇賀福神社}} (Kamakura City, Kanagawa Prefecture) * Shimizu Benzaiten Shrine (Saku City, Nagano Prefecture) * {{ill|Tenkawa Daibenzaiten Shrine|ja|天河大弁財天社}} (Tenkawa Village, Yoshino District, Nara Prefecture, one of Japan's Three Great Benzaiten Shrines){{efn2|The Benzaiten Shrine in Tenkawa Village is not normally open to the public and can only be viewed during the once-in-60-years grand unveiling (''gokaichō''). During this time, major events such as Noh performances and the ''Reitaisai'' (Grand Festival) are held, attracting tourists and worshippers from across the country to Tenkawa Village. Tenkawa Daibenzaiten Shrine is particularly popular among performing artists, with many prominent figures visiting from Tokyo and other regions. The most recent unveiling was on July 18, 2008.}} * {{ill|Koganeyama Shrine|ja|黄金山神社 (石巻市)}} (Ishinomaki City, Miyagi Prefecture, Kinkasan) * {{ill|Rokko Hime Shrine|ja|六甲比命神社}} (Nada Ward, Kobe City, Hyogo Prefecture, Rokkosan Town) – A theory suggests that Benzaiten = {{ill|Seoritsuhime|ja|瀬織津姫}}, whose mausoleum is believed to be here. * [[Benzaiten Shrine]]
For shrines dedicated to Ichikishimahime no Mikoto, refer to the {{ill|Munakata Three Goddesses|ja|宗像三女神}} or {{ill|Ichikishima Shrine|ja|市杵島神社}}.
